15 WHEREAS, the lack of dedicated capital funding for locally approved charter schools
16 hinders their ability to make long-term investments in infrastructure, address facility needs,
17 and ensure equity in educational environments; and
18 WHEREAS, it is in the best interest of the State of Georgia to evaluate the current funding
19 mechanisms for locally approved charter school capital improvements and explore policy
20 solutions to address current disparities.
21 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE:
22 (1) Creation of Senate study committee. There is created the Senate Study Committee
23 on Funding for Charter School Capital Improvements.
24 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of five members of the
25 Senate. Three members shall be appointed by the President of the Senate and two
26 members shall be appointed by the Minority Leader of the Senate. The President of the
27 Senate shall designate a member of the committee as chairperson of the committee.
28 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
29 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
30 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate, including but not limited
31 to the following:
32 (A) Reviewing current funding mechanisms for capital improvements in Georgia's
33 public schools and assessing their impact on charter schools;
34 (B) Examining disparities in capital funding between charter schools and traditional
35 public schools;
36 (C) Analyzing the challenges charter schools face in accessing state and local capital
37 funding, including E-SPLOST, bond financing, and capital outlay grants;
38 (D) Gathering testimony from charter school leaders, education stakeholders, and
39 financial experts to assess the impact of funding limitations; and
